<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12079l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12079l">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12079l"> 79(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ allows wife to marry</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Sa femme &hellip; lui avait demand&eacute; la permission de prendre un autre mari. Merlin le lui avait permis; m&ecirc;me il avait pouss&eacute; l&apos;indulgence jusqu&apos;&agrave; lui promettre son pr&eacute;sent de noces: &ldquo;Seulement, que ton nouvel &eacute;poux, dit-il, se garde bien de para&icirc;tre devant mes yeux; il lui arriverait malheur.&rdquo; Pr&eacute;venu du jour des noces par l&apos;&eacute;toile de V&eacute;nus, Merlin arrive <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &agrave; cheval sur un cerf, monture ordinaire de plusieurs grands personnages de la tradition celtique. <br><font color="green">[His wife, who did not like being a widow and a married woman at the same time, asked him permission to take another husband. <mark>Merlin gave the permission</mark>, and he went as far as to promise a wedding present: &ldquo;Just, tell your husband to keep out of my sight, lest some misfortune befall him.&rdquo; Informed of the wedding day by the star of Venus, Merlin arrived <mark>sitting on a stag</mark>, a common enough mount for several prominent figures of the Celtic tradition]</font> <small> [TLMM]Th&eacute;odore-Claude Hersart, Vicomte de La Villemarqu&eacute;, <cite a>Myrdhinn, ou l'enchanteur Merlin</cite></a> (1862) 125</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
